  "texts": [
    "This requires that for x ∈ A p, so x ̸ = ⊥, we haveh p (x) ̸ = ⊥ ′.",
    "Indeed, if h p (x) = ′ {x ′ | x ≤ h(x ′)} = ⊥ ′, then since h is complete, {h(x ′) | x ≤ h(x ′)} = ⊥, which implies x ≤ ⊥, contradicting x ̸ = ⊥.Since ⊥ is not in the domain of h p and ⊥ ′ is not in its range, we may writeh p (x) = ′ {x ′ ∈ A ′ p | x ⊑ h(x ′)}.Here ⊑ and ⊑ ′ are the refinement relations in A p and A ′ p, respectively, as in Definition 5.14.",
    "Now we make several observations about h p:(a) y ⊑ x implies h p (y) ⊑ ′ h p (x).",
    "For if y ⊑ x, then x ⊑ h(z ′) implies y ⊑ h(z ′), so {z ′ | x ⊑ h(z ′)} ⊆ {z ′ | y ⊑ h(z ′)}, which implies ′ {z ′ | y ⊑ h(z ′)} ⊑ ′ {z ′ | x ⊑ h(z ′)}, which means h p (y) ⊑ ′ h p (x).",
    "(b) h p (h(y ′)) ⊑ ′ y ′."
  ],
